This chapter covers the installation and configuration of Nagios and Zabbix on a Fedora Server for monitoring network health, server performance, and device availability.
Nagios: A powerful, extensible monitoring tool widely used for servers, network devices, and services.
Zabbix: A modern monitoring solution with a web-based frontend, offering templates, alerting, and performance graphs.
Using these tools allows administrators to detect, alert, and resolve issues proactively.

Installing and Configuring Nagios
................................
Step 1: Install Nagios
sudo dnf install nagios

Step 2: Install Additional Plugins
Nagios uses plugins to monitor different services:
sudo dnf install nagios-plugins-all

Step 3: Start Nagios Service
sudo systemctl start nagios

Step 4: Enable Nagios at Boot
sudo systemctl enable nagios

Step 5: Access Nagios Web Interface
Open a browser and go to:
http://<server-ip-or-domain>/nagios/
Default login credentials:
Username: nagiosadmin
Password: set during installation

Step 6: Configure Nagios
Configuration files are in:
sudo nano /etc/nagios/<config-file>.cfg
Define hosts, services, and notifications by editing the .cfg files.

 Installing and Configuring Zabbix
 ..................................
Step 1: Add Zabbix Repository
sudo dnf install https://repo.zabbix.com/zabbix/5.4/rhel/8/x86_64/zabbix-release-5.4-1.el8.noarch.rpm

Step 2: Install Zabbix Server, Web Frontend, and Agent
sudo dnf install zabbix-server-mysql zabbix-web-mysql zabbix-appliance

Step 3: Create Zabbix Database
Log in to MySQL/MariaDB:
mysql -u root -p

Run the following commands inside MySQL:
CREATE DATABASE zabbix CHARACTER SET utf8 COLLATE utf8_bin;
CREATE USER 'zabbix'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'your_password';
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON zabbix.* TO 'zabbix'@'localhost';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
EXIT;

Step 4: Import Zabbix Database Schema
zcat /usr/share/doc/zabbix-server-mysql*/create.sql.gz | mysql -uzabbix -p zabbix

Step 5: Configure Zabbix Server
Edit the server configuration:
sudo nano /etc/zabbix/zabbix_server.conf


Set the database password:
DBPassword=your_password

Step 6: Start and Enable Zabbix Services
sudo systemctl start zabbix-server zabbix-agent httpd
sudo systemctl enable zabbix-server zabbix-agent httpd

Step 7: Access Zabbix Web Interface
Open a browser:
http://<server-ip-or-domain>/zabbix


Default login:
Username: Admin
Password: zabbix

From the web interface, you can:
Add hosts
Create templates
Set up alerting and notifications

 NOTE:
Always secure your web interfaces with strong passwords.
Regularly update Nagios and Zabbix packages.
Tailor monitoring templates to your network and server environment.

Test alerts to ensure notifications are received promptly.
